# ------------------------------------------------------------
# PURPOSE
# ------------------------------------------------------------
The NIST 800-53 Engine ensures:
- Federal information system security compliance
- Comprehensive control implementation across 20 families
- Systematic evidence collection and management
- Support for FedRAMP, FISMA, and enterprise frameworks
- Continuous Authorization to Operate (ATO) readiness

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# NIST 800-53 REV 5 CONTROL FAMILIES
# ------------------------------------------------------------

## AC — Access Control
Controls: AC-1 through AC-25
Focus:
- Account management
- Access enforcement
- Information flow enforcement
- Separation of duties
- Least privilege
- Session controls
- Permitted actions without identification
- Remote access
- Wireless access
- Access control for mobile devices

## AT — Awareness and Training
Controls: AT-1 through AT-6
Focus:
- Security awareness training
- Role-based training
- Training records

## AU — Audit and Accountability
Controls: AU-1 through AU-16
Focus:
- Audit events and content
- Audit storage and retention
- Audit review, analysis, and reporting
- Audit reduction and report generation
- Time stamps and protection
- Non-repudiation
- Session audit
- Cross-organizational audit

## CA — Assessment, Authorization, and Monitoring
Controls: CA-1 through CA-9
Focus:
- Control assessments
- Plan of action and milestones
- Authorization decisions
- Continuous monitoring
- Penetration testing
- Internal system connections

## CM — Configuration Management
Controls: CM-1 through CM-14
Focus:
- Baseline configurations
- Configuration change control
- Security and privacy impact analysis
- Access restrictions for change
- Configuration settings
- Component inventory
- Software usage restrictions
- User-installed software

## CP — Contingency Planning
Controls: CP-1 through CP-13
Focus:
- Contingency plan
- Contingency training and testing
- Alternate storage, processing, and communication sites
- System recovery and reconstitution
- Backup and information recovery

## IA — Identification and Authentication
Controls: IA-1 through IA-12
Focus:
- User and device identification and authentication
- Authenticator management
- Authenticator feedback and cryptographic module authentication
- Re-authentication
- Identification and authentication (non-organizational users)

## IR — Incident Response
Controls: IR-1 through IR-10
Focus:
- Incident response training and testing
- Incident handling and monitoring
- Incident reporting
- Incident response assistance
- Incident response plan
- Information spillage response

## MA — Maintenance
Controls: MA-1 through MA-7
Focus:
- Controlled and timely maintenance
- Maintenance tools and personnel
- Nonlocal maintenance
- Maintenance personnel

## MP — Media Protection
Controls: MP-1 through MP-8
Focus:
- Media access, marking, storage
- Media transport and sanitization
- Media use and downgrading

## PE — Physical and Environmental Protection
Controls: PE-1 through PE-23
Focus:
- Physical access authorizations and control
- Access control for transmission
- Access control for output devices
- Monitoring physical access
- Visitor records
- Power equipment and cabling
- Emergency shutoff, power, and lighting
- Fire and water damage protection
- Temperature, humidity, and delivery/removal controls
- Alternate work sites and location of components

## PL — Planning
Controls: PL-1 through PL-11
Focus:
- System security and privacy plans
- Rules of behavior
- Security and privacy architectures
- Central management
- Baseline selection

## PM — Program Management
Controls: PM-1 through PM-32
Focus:
- Information security program plan
- Risk management strategy
- Enterprise architecture
- Critical infrastructure plan
- Insider threat program
- Supply chain risk management

## PS — Personnel Security
Controls: PS-1 through PS-9
Focus:
- Position risk designation
- Personnel screening
- Personnel termination and transfer
- Access agreements
- External personnel security
- Personnel sanctions

## PT — PII Processing and Transparency
Controls: PT-1 through PT-8
Focus:
- Authority to process PII
- Computer matching requirements
- Consent
- Privacy notice and specific categories of PII

## RA — Risk Assessment
Controls: RA-1 through RA-10
Focus:
- Risk assessment
- Security categorization
- Vulnerability monitoring and scanning
- Risk response
- Technical surveillance countermeasures

## SA — System and Services Acquisition
Controls: SA-1 through SA-23
Focus:
- Acquisition process
- Supply chain risk management
- System documentation and development process
- Developer configuration and testing
- Customized development
- Inspection of systems

## SC — System and Communications Protection
Controls: SC-1 through SC-51
Focus:
- Separation of functionality
- Security function isolation
- Denial-of-service protection
- Boundary protection
- Transmission and cryptographic protection
- Collaborative computing and public access protections
- Session and mobile code authenticity
- Secure name/address resolution
- Architecture and provisioning
- Heterogeneity

## SI — System and Information Integrity
Controls: SI-1 through SI-23
Focus:
- Flaw and malicious code protection
- Security alerts and advisories
- Security and privacy function verification
- Software, firmware, and information integrity
- Spam and spyware protection
- Information input, output, and error handling
- Memory protection and fail-safe procedures

## SR — Supply Chain Risk Management
Controls: SR-1 through SR-12
Focus:
- Supply chain risk management plan
- Supplier assessments and acquisition strategies
- Notification agreements and component authenticity
- Inspection of systems and tamper resistance

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# CAPABILITIES
# ------------------------------------------------------------

## 1. Control Mapping
Map EAOS configurations to:
- All 20 control families
- Individual control requirements
- Control enhancements
- Implementation status
- Baseline applicability (Low, Moderate, High)

## 2. Evidence Generator
Collect:
- System security plans
- Assessment reports
- Configuration baselines
- Audit logs
- Training records
- Incident reports
- POA&M documentation

## 3. Gap Analysis
Detect:
- Missing controls by baseline
- Partial implementations
- Controls without evidence
- Expired documentation
- Non-compliant configurations

## 4. POA&M Generator
Create:
- Plan of Action and Milestones
- Risk-prioritized remediation
- Milestone timelines
- Resource allocations
- Responsible parties

